1
00:00:00,669 --> 00:00:06,680
The MACD is very popular among traders, yet
there's more to using and understanding it

2
00:00:06,680 --> 00:00:08,330
than meets the eye.

3
00:00:08,330 --> 00:00:13,480
The MACD uses moving-average lines to illustrate
changes in price patterns.

4
00:00:13,480 --> 00:00:19,609
MACD is a great indicator to confirm the setups,
locate and follow the trends, no matter what

5
00:00:19,609 --> 00:00:21,490
trading system you trade.

6
00:00:21,490 --> 00:00:27,670
Among all the signals or patterns that MACD
makes, a MACD divergence is my favorite and

7
00:00:27,670 --> 00:00:31,610
the most reliable leading signals I could
get.

8
00:00:31,610 --> 00:00:37,960
A divergence in general occurs when the price
action is seeing lower lows while in a downtrend,

9
00:00:37,960 --> 00:00:41,260
but the indicator is not reflecting that move.

10
00:00:41,260 --> 00:00:46,149
Similarly, when the markets are trending higher,
you notice divergence when the price action

11
00:00:46,149 --> 00:00:52,049
is seen scaling higher highs but somehow the
indicator remains firm of the changes, and

12
00:00:52,049 --> 00:00:53,459
forms lower highs.

13
00:00:53,459 --> 00:00:58,730
So, when the price of an asset, such as a
stock or currency pair, is moving in one direction

14
00:00:58,730 --> 00:01:04,489
and the MACD's indicator line is moving in
the other, that's divergence.

15
00:01:04,489 --> 00:01:10,340
This type of signal is supposed to warn of
a price- direction reversal, but the signal

16
00:01:10,340 --> 00:01:14,549
can be misleading and inaccurate.

17
00:01:14,549 --> 00:01:20,320
Another type of divergence is when a security's
price reaches a new high (or a new low) level,

18
00:01:20,320 --> 00:01:22,789
but the MACD indicator doesn't.

19
00:01:22,789 --> 00:01:27,350
Essentially what it conveys is the shift in
the market momentum.

20
00:01:27,350 --> 00:01:32,470
After all, the markets are driven by momentum
and the momentum is the force that oscillates

21
00:01:32,470 --> 00:01:37,729
between highs and lows and thereby bringing
the changes in the price action.

22
00:01:37,729 --> 00:01:42,600
Traditionally, this would indicate that the
price's direction is losing momentum and is

23
00:01:42,600 --> 00:01:44,179
priming for a reversal.

24
00:01:44,179 --> 00:01:49,759
But, by its own, this can also prove to be
an unreliable trading signal.

25
00:01:49,759 --> 00:01:54,759
While you don't need to understand the math
that underlies the calculation of the MACD,

26
00:01:54,759 --> 00:02:00,829
by understanding more about how the MACD indicator
works, you'll be better positioned to avoid

27
00:02:00,829 --> 00:02:07,700
getting fooled by its false signals or lack
of signals, such as when the price turns but

28
00:02:07,700 --> 00:02:10,580
the MACD doesn't provide any warning.

29
00:02:10,580 --> 00:02:15,830
So, let’s discuss about the main issues
with MACD divergences.

30
00:02:15,830 --> 00:02:16,830
1.

31
00:02:16,830 --> 00:02:23,470
First, MACD divergence after a sharp move
Monitoring the MACD indicator in relation

32
00:02:23,470 --> 00:02:29,420
to price action reveals a few problems which
could affect traders who rely on the MACD

33
00:02:29,420 --> 00:02:30,879
divergence tool.

34
00:02:30,879 --> 00:02:36,342
A divergence pattern between the two MACD
lines will almost always occur right after

35
00:02:36,342 --> 00:02:39,840
a sharp price move, whether higher or lower.

36
00:02:39,840 --> 00:02:45,590
Determining whether a price move is sharp,
slow, large or small requires looking at the

37
00:02:45,590 --> 00:02:50,140
velocity and magnitude of the price movements
around it.

38
00:02:50,140 --> 00:02:56,060
Price momentum can't continue forever so as
soon as the price begins to level off, the

39
00:02:56,060 --> 00:03:02,960
MACD trend lines will diverge (for example,
go up, even if the price is still dropping).

40
00:03:02,960 --> 00:03:08,390
After a strong price rally, the MACD divergence
is no longer useful.

41
00:03:08,390 --> 00:03:14,799
By dropping, while the price continues to
move higher or move sideways, the MACD is

42
00:03:14,799 --> 00:03:21,060
showing momentum has slowed but it doesn't
indicate a reversal.

43
00:03:21,060 --> 00:03:26,489
In this example, the EUR/USD is falling, yet
the MACD is rising.

44
00:03:26,489 --> 00:03:31,629
Had a trader assumed that the rising MACD
was a positive sign, they may have exited

45
00:03:31,629 --> 00:03:35,760
their short trade, missing out on additional
profit.

46
00:03:35,760 --> 00:03:40,519
Or they may have taken a long trade, even
though the price action showed a significant

47
00:03:40,519 --> 00:03:47,530
downtrend and no signs of a reversal (no higher
swing highs or higher swing lows to indicate

48
00:03:47,530 --> 00:03:49,969
an end to the downtrend).

49
00:03:49,969 --> 00:03:55,400
That doesn't mean divergence can't or won't
signal the occasional reversal, but it must

50
00:03:55,400 --> 00:03:58,750
be taken with a grain of salt after a big
move.

51
00:03:58,750 --> 00:04:05,019
Since divergence occurs after almost every
big move, and most big moves aren't immediately

52
00:04:05,019 --> 00:04:11,730
reversed right after, if you assume that divergence,
in this case, means a reversal is coming,

53
00:04:11,730 --> 00:04:16,200
you could get yourself into a lot of losing
trades.

54
00:04:16,200 --> 00:04:17,820
2.

55
00:04:17,820 --> 00:04:22,350
Problems with divergence between MACD highs
(or lows)

56
00:04:22,350 --> 00:04:28,470
Traders also compare prior highs on the MACD
with current highs or prior lows with current

57
00:04:28,470 --> 00:04:29,470
lows.

58
00:04:29,470 --> 00:04:35,191
For example, if the price moves above a prior
high, traders will watch for the MACD to also

59
00:04:35,191 --> 00:04:37,570
move above its prior high.

60
00:04:37,570 --> 00:04:42,700
If it doesn't, that's a divergence or a traditional
warning signal of a reversal.

61
00:04:42,700 --> 00:04:47,030
This signal is also related to the problem
discussed before.

62
00:04:47,030 --> 00:04:52,890
A lower MACD high-price level shows the price
didn't have the same velocity it had last

63
00:04:52,890 --> 00:04:59,110
time it moved higher (it may have moved less,
or it may have moved slower), but that doesn't

64
00:04:59,110 --> 00:05:01,220
necessarily indicate a reversal.

65
00:05:01,220 --> 00:05:07,340
As discussed above, a sharp price move will
cause a large move in the MACD, larger than

66
00:05:07,340 --> 00:05:11,140
what is caused by slower price moves.

67
00:05:11,140 --> 00:05:16,690
An asset's price can move higher or lower,
slowly, for very long periods of time.

68
00:05:16,690 --> 00:05:23,970
If this occurs after a steeper move (more
distance covered in less time), then the MACD

69
00:05:23,970 --> 00:05:29,190
will show divergence for much of the time
the price is slowly marching higher (relative

70
00:05:29,190 --> 00:05:31,690
to the prior sharp move).

71
00:05:31,690 --> 00:05:38,160
If a trader assumes a lower MACD high means
the price will reverse, a valuable opportunity

72
00:05:38,160 --> 00:05:44,960
may be missed to stay long and collect more
profit from the slower increase higher.

73
00:05:44,960 --> 00:05:50,910
Or worse, the trader may take a short position
into a strong uptrend, with little evidence

74
00:05:50,910 --> 00:05:57,870
to support the trade except for an indicator
which isn't useful in this situation.

75
00:05:57,870 --> 00:06:00,210
This example shows a downtrend.

76
00:06:00,210 --> 00:06:06,120
The downtrend is caused by sharp downward
moves, followed by slower downward moves.

77
00:06:06,120 --> 00:06:12,630
This results in divergence when the next price
wave isn't as sharp, but in no way indicates

78
00:06:12,630 --> 00:06:15,020
a reversal on the MACD.

79
00:06:15,020 --> 00:06:21,020
MACD divergence was present this whole time,
yet the price dropped all day.

80
00:06:21,020 --> 00:06:27,440
If monitoring divergence, an entire day of
profits on the downside would have been missed.

81
00:06:27,440 --> 00:06:32,960
Another problem with watching for this type
of divergence is that it often isn't present

82
00:06:32,960 --> 00:06:35,880
when an actual price reversal occurs.

83
00:06:35,880 --> 00:06:41,580
Therefore, we have an indicator which provides
many false signals (divergence occurs, but

84
00:06:41,580 --> 00:06:47,960
price doesn't reverse), but also fails to
provide signals on many actual price reversals

85
00:06:47,960 --> 00:06:55,380
So, having these 2 MACD problems in mind,
how you improve the accuracy rate of spotting

86
00:06:55,380 --> 00:06:58,650
divergences correctly using this indicator?

87
00:06:58,650 --> 00:07:02,250
I use 3 steps:
First one.

88
00:07:02,250 --> 00:07:06,840
It’s safe to say we must focus on the price
action first, instead of divergence.

89
00:07:06,840 --> 00:07:13,740
For a downtrend to reverse, the price must
make a higher swing high and/or a higher swing

90
00:07:13,740 --> 00:07:14,900
low.

91
00:07:14,900 --> 00:07:21,340
To reverse an uptrend, the price must make
a lower swing high and/or a lower swing low.

92
00:07:21,340 --> 00:07:25,330
Until these occur, a price reversal isn't
present.

93
00:07:25,330 --> 00:07:29,430
Whether divergence is present or not isn't
important.

94
00:07:29,430 --> 00:07:34,520
Traders make money off price movements, not
MACD movements.

95
00:07:34,520 --> 00:07:35,520
The second step.

96
00:07:35,520 --> 00:07:42,020
I look for double divergence patterns, meaning
i want to see a divergence on both the histogram

97
00:07:42,020 --> 00:07:44,640
and on the signal and MACD line.

98
00:07:44,640 --> 00:07:46,020
Third step.

99
00:07:46,020 --> 00:07:51,030
With the creation of a double divergence on
the charts, i prefer to draw a trend line

100
00:07:51,030 --> 00:07:54,410
on the charts and enter after a breakout.

101
00:07:54,410 --> 00:07:59,640
This way, my stop loss is optimized below
or above the breakout and the entry points

102
00:07:59,640 --> 00:08:01,360
are clearly identified.

103
00:08:01,360 --> 00:08:07,800
Keep in mind that a trend might continue over
an extended period even after a double divergence.

104
00:08:07,800 --> 00:08:13,770
So it goes without saying that your stops
should be in place at all times to act as

105
00:08:13,770 --> 00:08:19,410
safety net against any potential misreading
or miscalculation of risks.

106
00:08:19,410 --> 00:08:25,910
Another interesting factor, to notice in case
of a double divergence, is volumes will decrease

107
00:08:25,910 --> 00:08:28,000
when the second divergence is underway.

108
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:34,149
Thus, it is a point where the momentum and
the volume seem to arrive at common grounds

109
00:08:34,149 --> 00:08:36,050
to represent a specific price action phenomenon.

110
00:08:36,050 --> 00:08:41,620
Here’s visa on a 15-min time frame.

111
00:08:41,620 --> 00:08:45,550
We have a first divergence on the histogram
here.

112
00:08:45,550 --> 00:08:50,050
The second divergence on the MACD line here.

113
00:08:50,050 --> 00:08:56,340
The market was making higher highs and higher
lows, so in order to trade the double MACD

114
00:08:56,340 --> 00:09:00,360
divergence, we needed the price to record
a lower low.

115
00:09:00,360 --> 00:09:05,490
Which it did, and at the same time, we had
the 3rd step completed, as the trend line

116
00:09:05,490 --> 00:09:08,699
marking the uptrend was broken to the downside.

117
00:09:08,699 --> 00:09:15,790
With all 3 conditions met, a short after the
breakout was a high probability trade.

118
00:09:15,790 --> 00:09:23,389
So we combined price action, with the MACD,
to find a decent short trade.

119
00:09:23,389 --> 00:09:27,540
The same pattern but on a downtrend.

120
00:09:27,540 --> 00:09:30,380
The histogram divergence.

121
00:09:30,380 --> 00:09:32,779
The MACD line divergence.

122
00:09:32,779 --> 00:09:36,350
A higher swing high.

123
00:09:36,350 --> 00:09:39,319
And the downslope trend line breakout.

124
00:09:39,319 --> 00:09:41,720
Perfect entry.

125
00:09:41,720 --> 00:09:53,699
Here are other examples of double MACD divergence
trades.

126
00:09:53,699 --> 00:10:07,529
It goes without saying that the price action
needs to be followed after you’re in a trade.

127
00:10:07,529 --> 00:10:12,779
It does not mean that you have to be up and
awake in front of the screen all day monitoring

128
00:10:12,779 --> 00:10:18,230
ever pip move but at the same time, you must
remember never to lose sight of the primary

129
00:10:18,230 --> 00:10:24,220
levels and how they need to be capitalized
in conjunction with the new trend in the market,

130
00:10:24,220 --> 00:10:28,290
which hopefully started after the MACD divergence.

131
00:10:28,290 --> 00:10:32,510
And remember not to have irrational expectation
from the market.

132
00:10:32,510 --> 00:10:38,040
Set up realistic profit and loss targets and
work towards realizing the profit.

133
00:10:38,040 --> 00:10:44,110
I like to use this double divergence strategy
in my day trading activity, but it can also

134
00:10:44,110 --> 00:10:47,499
be used with as a swing trading tool.

135
